---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
---

<Base
  title="AI Toolkit | Willy W."
  description="The exact stack and division of labor Willy W. uses to build like a team: Claude architects and reviews, Codex builds, Obsidian remembers."
>
  <div class="page-hero">
    <p class="kicker">toolkit</p>
    <h1>The tools are not the story. The workflow is.</h1>
    <p>
      Anyone can open a chat window. The difference between "AI-assisted" and shipping
      real systems is structure: separated roles, strict scope, independent checks, and
      memory that outlives the session. This is the exact setup I use.
    </p>
  </div>

  <section aria-labelledby="tool-list-title">
    <div class="sec-head">
      <h2 id="tool-list-title">Stack</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="page-stack">
      <article class="page-card">
        <h3>Claude: architect &amp; reviewer</h3>
        <p>
          Plans the system, writes the spec, and challenges my assumptions before code
          exists. Then it reviews every diff after Codex writes it: scope adherence,
          correctness, and an independent build. Claude never reviews code it wrote
          itself; that's the whole point of having two models.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="page-card">
        <h3>Codex: builder</h3>
        <p>
          Takes one tightly scoped prompt at a time ("do X and ONLY X") and turns it into
          working code with its own verification pass. One phase, one clean commit. The
          strictness isn't distrust; it's what keeps every change reviewable.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="page-card">
        <h3>Obsidian + markdown: memory</h3>
        <p>
          Specs, decisions with their reasoning, status, and handoff notes live as plain
          files in the repo and in a structured vault. Chat history is disposable; files
          are not. Any new session, or an entirely different model, starts from facts.
        </p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section aria-labelledby="practices-title">
    <div class="sec-head">
      <h2 id="practices-title">The practices that make it work</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="page-stack">
      <article class="page-card">
        <h3>Strict phase scoping</h3>
        <p>
          Every build prompt defines exactly one phase and explicitly lists what is out of
          scope. Eager models over-build; pre-agreed boundaries keep the diff small enough
          to actually review.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="page-card">
        <h3>Independent verification</h3>
        <p>
          "Build passes" is a claim, not a fact — until the reviewer runs the build itself,
          reads the diff, and greps for rule violations. Trust me becomes check me, and the
          checks are cheap.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="page-card">
        <h3>File-based handoffs</h3>
        <p>
          Specs travel in one file, completion reports in another, both committed to git.
          Either side of the workflow can be swapped for a newer model without losing the
          project. This very site was built that way, and its
          <a href="/blog/two-ai-dev-team/">commit history shows it</a>.
        </p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section aria-labelledby="safety-title">
    <div class="sec-head">
      <h2 id="safety-title">The safety layer</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="page-stack">
      <article class="page-card">
        <h3>Rules the model can't override</h3>
        <p>
          Every agent on my machine runs behind a deterministic guard: a pre-execution hook
          that checks each action against a fixed rule set before it happens. The rules hold
          even when the model is wrong, confused, or being manipulated, because the
          enforcement sits outside the model instead of depending on it. The same rails are
          mirrored to every agent I run, so switching tools never means losing the protections.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="page-card">
        <h3>External content is data, not instructions</h3>
        <p>
          Web pages, emails, files and scraped posts are things my agents read, never things
          they obey. If fetched content says "run this command", it gets flagged and shown to
          me, not followed. The rule earns its keep in practice: when a URL arrived with a
          live login token embedded in it, the fetch was refused and the token rotated,
          instead of the credential leaking into a third-party request.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="page-card">
        <h3>Remove the capability, don't trust the promise</h3>
        <p>
          Where the stakes are real, I take the ability away rather than rely on a rule. The
          <a href="/projects/spot-grid-trading-bot/">grid bot's</a> key can sign orders but
          not withdrawals. Advisory agents run with a file-only toolset, so placing a trade
          isn't disobedience, it's impossible. And anything outward-facing, a publish, a
          push, a message, waits for a human yes. Every time.
        </p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>
